  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3823958672" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3823958672" />
    <a title="Logan Grant" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4635083-logan-grant"><img alt="Logan Grant" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1613701469p2/4635083.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3823958672?book_show_action=true">Feb 18, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Logan Grant" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Logan Grant" href="/user/show/4635083-logan-grant">Logan Grant</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/15981162-the-civil-war">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3823958672" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7956626374628664963"><a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/10252344.The_Civil_War_A_Narrative_Volume_1_Fort_Sumter_to_Perryville' title='The Civil War A Narrative Volume 1 Fort Sumter to Perryville by Shelby Foote' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Civil War: A Narrative: Volume 1: Fort Sumter to Perryville</a><br/>Published: 1958<br/>My background on the subject:<br/>1) The Impending Crisis (David M. Potter, 1976)<br/>2) Grant (Jean Edward Smith, 2002)<br/>3) Lincoln (David Herbert Donald, 1996)<br/>4) Battle Cry of Freedom (James McPherson, 1988)<br/><br/>“You are bound to fail. Only in your spirit and determination are you prepared for war. In all else you are totally unprepared and with a bad cause to start with. At first you will make headway, but as your limited resources </span>
  <span id="freeText7956626374628664963" style="display:none"><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/10252344.The_Civil_War_A_Narrative_Volume_1_Fort_Sumter_to_Perryville" title="The Civil War A Narrative Volume 1 Fort Sumter to Perryville by Shelby Foote" rel="nofollow noopener">The Civil War: A Narrative: Volume 1: Fort Sumter to Perryville</a><br />Published: 1958<br />My background on the subject:<br />1) The Impending Crisis (David M. Potter, 1976)<br />2) Grant (Jean Edward Smith, 2002)<br />3) Lincoln (David Herbert Donald, 1996)<br />4) Battle Cry of Freedom (James McPherson, 1988)<br /><br />“You are bound to fail. Only in your spirit and determination are you prepared for war. In all else you are totally unprepared and with a bad cause to start with. At first you will make headway, but as your limited resources begin to fail, shut out from the markets of Europe as you will be, your cause will begin to wane. If your people will but stop and think, they must see that in the end they will surely fail.”<br />	- William Tecumseh Sherman to a Southerner on Christmas Eve, 1860<br /><br />“We may be annihilated, but we cannot be conquered.”<br />	-Albert Sidney Johnston, 1862<br /><br />The Civil War was many things. An unavoidable war between two societies that could not coexist under the same government. A failure to compromise. The violent resolution of an innate conflict between self-evident truth and human bondage. A tragic game of chicken between two factions that woefully underestimated one another’s determination. A noble crusade of liberation that would act as an antidote to the mental and spiritual poisons of chattel slavery. Well, maybe not that last one.<br /><br />For all the things the Civil War was or wasn’t, in this book it is a military contest between men of sincere- if misguided- principles. The chief opponents were Abraham Lincoln and Jefferson Davis, who were each fighting a war, as Foote insightfully describes it “for survival – survival of the South, as Davis saw it: survival of the Union, as Lincoln saw it – with the added paradox that, while neither of the two leaders believed victory for his side meant extinction for the other, each insisted that the reverse was true.” Just as these men differed in their views of the Civil War, I expect every reader will also bring with them their own views on what the Civil War was and how it should be depicted. If you are looking for a simple epic with heroes and villains, then I must insist that not only is this book not for you, but neither is the study of history itself. Reducing real people into fanciful roles as agents of good or evil contributes to ignorance, rather than relieving it.<br /><br />Foote doesn’t define individuals by single acts of heroism, inadequacy, ingenuity, or poltroonery, nor does he try to put them into a category of righteous or iniquitous. His first ambition is to tell the story truly, but well. I think in close second is his desire to honor these men and their deeds. If, however, you’re worried about this being misty-eyed hagiography, then fear not. A surprising amount of this book dwells on the causes and consequences of the many mistakes, miscommunications, and failures made by the men responsible for the fates of their fellow soldiers. The Seven Days battles were practically a ballet of dumpster fires. Despite their many shortcomings, it is hard not to sympathize with men who were trying to do their best for the causes they believed in. This is especially easy because Foote tiptoes around the repulsiveness of racism and chattel slavery. The former is barely mentioned and the latter is essentially treated as an abstraction. Perhaps he’s reserved those for the two volumes that follow, but he seems to be deliberately keeping the proverbial turd out of the punchbowl. Knowing Foote from his role in Ken Burn’s Civil War documentary series, I was not surprised by this. Nor am I bothered by it. Not every history book needs to cover every aspect of its subject. I am perfectly content with a book that tries to evenhandedly focus on the virtues of its subjects.<br /><br />The task he gives himself in this book is honoring the men who fought this conflict in a dynamic and enthralling narrative. It is an outstanding book, written with great care by an outstanding author. Combining the dramatic approach of a novelist with the didactic approach of a historian, Foote makes an already thrilling subject even more so. One of the strengths Foote brings as a novelist – as opposed to what we expect from a conventional historian – is his ability and inclination to use drama to draw the reader in and make a greater impact upon them when the unexpected occurs. Indeed, one of the greatest distinctions between Foote and other authors of history I have read is that the former can write each scene in a vacuum, whereas the latter connect events with those past and future. For example, there was a point at which Lincoln was rearranging the leadership of the military so that all of his fighting generals were given command and other generals who had turned caution into a vice were given their leave. Grant up to that point had displayed little concern for anything that wasn’t strictly offensive, but after a few disappointing battles in the midst of a disappointing assignment, his dispatches to Lincoln did not sound like the tenacious bringer-of-the-storm that had caused the President to protect Grant from the constant (mostly false) attacks on his character and performance. Lincoln had said, “I need this man, he fights”, but he was worried that Grant may have gone the way of other formerly-bold generals once given command. Three other books I have read have covered this period and in all it was described from the outset as a temporary deviation from the inevitable (which it was). Foote the novelist conveys the anxiety that Lincoln was experiencing due to Grant’s apparent loss of aggression as a serious threat to the success of the Union (which it was). The unfamiliar reader wonders what will become of Grant, so that when he gets his groove back (groove here meaning unrelenting desire to fight confederates wherever he can find them), it is all the more exhilarating. On the other hand, in some instances it seems that Foote is oversimplifying or omitting information in order to suit the structure of the narrative. For example, the relationship between Jefferson Davis and Joseph E. Johnston is characterized in seemingly contrary ways throughout the book. Upon further review, I discovered that there was nuance by which all of it could fit together but while reading the book I never felt that the nuances were address and so contradictory elements of a complex relationship appeared unreconciled.<br /><br />Throughout the book, Foote shifts between the perspectives of the North and South. The vantage point he uses at any given event is clearly dictated by his fidelity to good storytelling instead of some broad-scale thesis. The South seems to get a majority of the attention, but I have no problem with this because the Confederacy is more foreign to me than the Union is. Jefferson Davis was fighting for a cause that is so much harder for me to comprehend than the cause Abraham Lincoln fought for. Of course, many of their contemporaries would probably share my sentiment. Although this book sticks primarily to the military events of the Civil War and doesn’t present a comprehensive portrait of the culture of the Confederacy, in its many anecdotes there are meaningful insights into that menagerie of anachronism. Furthermore, the military leadership of the Confederacy was so full of idiosyncratic personalities that as a reader you’re always intrigued for the next kooky incident. For example, I am now more surprised when Stonewall Jackson remains awake during a major battle than when he takes a nice little siesta in the middle of bloody warfare. <br /><br />The Civil War is a roust subject, and as much as I love this book, I would recommend that someone new to it start with something that had a broader scope than Shelby Foote’s narrative. If, however, you are only interested in military history, then this would be the perfect starting place. In any case, I strongly recommend this book and look forward to the next volume.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7956626374628664963" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

